AGI - The oath of new 34 guards of the Pontifical Swiss Guard will take place on 6 May at 5 pm in the Courtyard of San Damaso of the Apostolic Palace in the Vatican. Every year, the new guards swear on the occasion of the anniversary of the sack of Rome, where 189 Swiss Guards defended Pope Clement VII against the army of Charles V. The oath takes place on the flag of the Body of the Pontifical Swiss Guards and in the presence of the representative of the Pontiff, Monsignor Edgar Pena Parra, Replaced for General Affairs of the Secretariat of State.
&nbsp;
The guards thus swear to protect and defend the Pope in office and all his legitimate successors, even at the risk of his life, as they have done in the past their valiant and faithful ancestors. On the day before the oath, on May 5, the Vespers will be celebrated at 5 p.m. in the Church "Santa Maria della Pietà in Campo Santo Teutonico" and to follow is previewed the deposition of the crown in honor of the fallen of May 6, 1527 with conferment of the honors in the "Piazza dei Protomartiri Romani" by Monsignor Edgar Pena Parra. On the day of the oath, on the morning, the Mass will be celebrated in St. Peter's, by Cardinal Pietro Parolin, Vatican Secretary of State. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
&nbsp;
The oath will take place in a festive atmosphere. The guards wear the "Gran Gala", the gala uniform with armor, which is worn for the papal blessing "Urbi et Orbi", at Christmas and Easter. There will be a delegation of the Swiss Confederation, led by the President of the Confederation Viola Amherd with the President of the National Council Eric Nussbaumer and the President of the Council of States Brigitte Eva Herzog.
&nbsp;
Moreover, the head of the Army will be represented by Brigadier Jacques Frederic Rudin, Deputy Chief of Staff of the Army, and will be present the representative of the Swiss Episcopal Conference, Monsignor Felix Gmur (president), Bishop of Basel. This year's host canton delegation, Basel Campaign, is led by the president of the cantonal government, Monica Gschwind. It will be possible to watch the Jurament streaming on the official website of the Pontifical Swiss Guard: www.guardiasvizzera.ch.
&nbsp;
The oldest army in the world, founded by Pope Julius II on 22 January 1506, is responsible for the protection of the Pope and his residence. Guided by Colonel Christoph Graf (LU), he has the task of controlling access to the Vatican and the Apostolic Palace, to ensure order and representation during papal ceremonies and state receptions and to protect the College of Cardinals during the vacant seat. The Body includes guards from all the language regions of Switzerland. Most members of the Corps are from the canton of Freiburg (17), followed by the cantons of Valais (16) and St Gall (13). &nbsp;
